2023-11-17  James Gallagher  <jgallagher@opendap.org>

	Comments and use of std::make_shared<http::url>().

	Ngap file cache (#847)
	This is the culmination of the work on DMR++ caching.

	A memory cache is used by each process to hold DMR++ documents for
	fast reuse.  Timing data shows the memory cache returns hits in
	~100uS. This is backed up by a file cache that can be accessed across
	all the processes on a given host (and across hosts if the file system
	supports NFS - which AWS's EFS does). Timing data shows cache hits for
	the file cache return items in ~1mS. Network access has been
	refactored so that the DMR++ is read from the wire directly into a C++
	string object and this takes about 500mS without the overhead of
	authentication (i.e., in tests where we use OPeNDAP's S3 bucket and do
	not rely on a web service for credentials or 'URL signing').

2023-11-14  James Gallagher  <jgallagher@opendap.org>

	File cache (#837)

	This is a simple cache for files. Its API is limited to get(key,
	&item), put(key, filename), del(key), clear(), purge(), and
	initialize(...). For all of these operations, the cache is locked.
	The get() operation returns _item_ with a valid open file descriptor
	to the file that is locked using a shared lock. When item is
	destroyed, the lock is cleared. There is a second version of put()
	that takes/returns a &PutItem that holds an open file descriptor that
	other code can write to. When the PutItem instance is destroyed, the
	fd is closed and the exclusive lock on the file is released. The cache
	is process- and thread-safe.
	
